Notice the lack of <code>&#34;</code> around the <code>cour.ttf</code> part,
this is, because, when using <code>&#34;</code>, the CSS rendering engine uses the conventional of CSS3,
in which the <code>local()</code> is a real function, in which the processing of the argument is as STRING.

By ommitting the <code>&#34;</code>: <code>local</code> is no longer a function but a more complex directive, in which the argument might be URI or URN, which is a global OS identifier, or even a path.
 - - Using this insight I am permitting parsing of the argument as local-path (which is safe to use).

Lastly the base64 representation of the TTF-binary content (it is US-ASCII),
which will only be rendered as last-resort. Still won't be easy on broadband since it is actually loads a large amount of data.
